* Come Tees, founded by Sonya Sombreuil back in 2009, is near synonymous with LA streetwear. And not very long ago, they were able to take their talents to new mediums, as Converse commissioned the label for a series of customized sneakers. Fall 2022 simply offers Sombreuil and her team yet another opportunity to express themselves, which they‚Äôve more than done atop two of the footwear brand‚Äôs most iconic silhouettes: the Chuck 70 and One Star. Compared to Come Tees‚Äô previous efforts, this collection is much more reserved. The orange canvas base of the Chuck 70, for example, is replete with negative space, a stark contrast to the all-over prints of what came before. Here, they‚Äôve applied leather applique and silver studs to the shoe‚Äôs lateral side, hastily-drawn text and art to the medial and outsole, and branding down the heel. The accompanying One Star features similar details and colors atop and adjacent to its grey suede base.

description:
selling this new pair of sneakers that was in my closet for a couple of years. I'd rather have someone wear it than being in the closet...
The Denim Tears and Converse collaboration, released in October 2021 cemented founder Tremaine Emory‚Äôs legacy as a multi-hyphenate. Acting as an ambidextrous call to arms, in the sense that the printed design does not only commemorate Black suffering but also encourages the youth to proverbially raise their hands and vote, Denim Tears and Converse have showcased the groundbreaking possibilities of what happens when you shatter the backboards between disciplines. Eluding to the fact that a Denim Tears collaboration is proof that it‚Äôs no more trend - the politics, fashion, music, art and culture hybrid is the indisputable future. The collaboration consisted of Converse x Denim Tears reimagined Chuck 70 High and Low silhouettes, mixing the David Hammons African-American Flag to the Marcus Garvey Pan-African Flag, whilst Emory held his cards close to his chest as he is so often does when designing a Denim Tears product, in paying homage to the Liberty Rock, where he grew up in St Albans, Queens, New York. The black, green and red African-American tropes evoke the collaborations multilayered culture ‚Äòmash-up.‚Äô Symbolising Tremaine Emory and Denim Tears‚Äô former-alter-ego-now- creative-playground visual labyrinthine and mindset maxim; create a product of desirability, spread the message, garner the role of the ‚Äòvoice of the voiceless‚Äô and do it all whilst dunking high in a pair of Chuck 70‚Äôs.
